column18: Less of the theatrical, mind theory and such that we will never remembers.  The stories and metaphors help along with multiple strategies.  What coaches did that worked sticks in our minds.
column19: The 3 levels of coaching does give you a deeper understanding of what you are coaching and why you coach.  It gives you some things to try with your team and some good ways to connect to your players outside of the sport they are playing.  The 3rd level gets a little daunting as you are trying to understand the authors say basically the same thing in many different ways to make a whole level out of it.  The 3rd level can be summed up pretty easy and probably doesnt need so much video and persuasion.

column18: The course has quite a bit of good information. I found a lot of it reassuring with what my beliefs are, but time is always a factor. As I watched many videos I found myself thinking that coaches know or see most of this, but I am not always sure the parents do. Maybe it would be good to get a 3D Parenting class started. We can bring parents into our programs, but ultimately the majority are still there for their child and gone after the season is over.

column19: This course has been absolutely incredible. The 3D framework is exactly what this generation of coaches need. The course has renewed my perspective as a coach and has opened my eyes to the areas where I have fallen short. The content is meaningful and applicable and the course flows smoothly. One of my favorite parts of the course is how it walks you through writing your transformational purpose statement. I am so pumped about my transformational purpose statement that I now have written (thanks to the course) that will guide my coaching. I cannot wait to start applying the strategies I have learned to my program. Well done!

column19: This was so well put together. It was obvious that there was a lot of passion and love that went in to this. I really appreciated the suggested activities and real world examples that were given throughout the modules. These are things I am so excited about implementing and have already started discussing with my coaching staff. Thank you so much for putting together such an incredible program!

column7:
Appoquinimink High School encourages​ ​participation​ ​in​ ​co-curricular programs​ ​as​ ​part​ ​of​ ​the​ ​comprehensive​ ​educational​ ​experience​. We​ ​believe involvement​ ​in​ ​these​ ​activities​ ​fosters​ ​unity,​ ​perseverance,​ ​and​ ​self​ ​discipline. The AHS Athletics Department’s expectations,​ ​in​ ​and​ ​out​ ​of​ ​the​ ​classroom,​ ​align​ not only with our school’s mission and core values, but ​with​ ​the​ Appoquinimink School ​District’s​ ​goals​ ​and objectives​ ​in​ ​order​ ​to​ ​achieve​ ​a​ ​high​ ​level​ ​of​ ​integrity​ ​and​ ​ethical​ ​responsibility.
To​ ​ensure​ ​the​ ​success​ ​of​ ​our​ ​students-athletes, we​ ​expect​ ​our​ ​coaches,​ ​staff,​ ​student- athletes,​ ​families, and our spectators​ ​to​ ​exemplify​ ​sportsmanship​ ​and​ ​upstanding​ ​character at all times.

column19: Just three years ago I had no intent to coach let alone becoming a head coach.  Having helped coach a youth program as part of student athlete coaches giving back to build the program I was comfortable with just helping.  I soon concluded that the other coaches not only didnt have experience playing the sport they were coaching but no experience coaching other than helping for a year or two with the current program.  To add to it the head coach was over commited to other programs and state level youth programs and was looking to find a suitable replacement.  I started making notes to what we should practice and how we should condition and that led to me being asked to take the team over.  It started off well and great effort and improvement however my skills as a coach were from twenty years ago as a highschool student and more suited for highschool athelets and adult learning.  Looking back I seen what this coures considers 3D coaching but didn't really acknowledge how and why.  As I found training courses for myself and my assistant coaches I found this course and not only does it follow teachings of my professional life but what I was exposed to long ago.  The intent is not only will the assistant coaches complete the sport specific certifications I have already mandated but also work their way to completing this course to ensure we are focused on the athletes developement not just in sport but in life.  Our program is an investment in the future program not a sell out results now program.  This course along with the parents training will be the cornerstone to guiding this program and rebuilding the community.

column7: To provide an environment where Student/Athletes embrace a trajectory of continuous  self-improvement with Integrity, Ethics, and Service in mind.
column18:
I find value in the connecting stories/presentations at the end of each module.  They remind me of Ted Talks.  I processed the 3-D material but I will remember the presentations.  When the time is right I will recall the presentations and use them to serve as a validating foundation for what we are about to do. 

I would keep the slides concise and to the point and add the commentary contained in the slides to the Ted Talk format.  All of the information is important. Personally, I feel more engaged when I am watching the presentation at the end than when I am watching the instructional slides.  There is a certain anticipation about them, I found myself leaning in and wondering what golden nugget of information is just ahead.  I also was reflecting during the presentation slides and drawing connections to my own experience.  I found them to be a powerful learning tool.

I also found value when I had a chance to write a response as part of a learning check.
column19:
This is very difficult material to cover in an online course.  

Many of the 3-D principles lend themselves to a live conversation or presentation.  I feel that the 3-D staff did an excellent job of covering meaningful material in a challenging format (online learning).  

I am looking forward to receiving the online news letters and communications from the 3-D staff.  I think it will help me keep focus on what is really important during the up-coming competitive season.  Thank you for providing that option!

column18: I think it was Module 10, but there was a question and there was only one answer, “reality check,” which looked like an incomplete answer list. Also, the video clip in Module 16.5, of the two teams coming together to pay money to the coach with the blood cancer, did not fully work.  The audio of the players speaking did not come through.
column19:
I loved the speakers, Jeff, Mark, and Wes.  I think the videographer did a tremendous job of putting it all together.  I really enjoyed the lesson plans and the formulas/charts that went along with the process.

I do not believe that all of the topics are novel in this program, but I DO agree that they are very important and topical.  I really enjoyed the mentality of reaching a player's heart and mind, and not just their physical ability.  I would recommend this program to a new coach, or a coach that is trying to better his/herself!

column18: I do believe most people play sports because they want too.  But, some are experimenting, playing just to play, and do not have the same desires as other players who love the sport. I do not believe this is true and needs time, repetition, and readiness to develop this passion.

column19: I am overwhelmed by the emotional and spiritual impact this course has had on me. I started this journey before I came across 3D Coaching when I read Joe Ehrmann's book  "Inside-Out Coaching" and I am very glad and thankful to God that I was introduced to the 3D Coaching program.  3D Coaching certification course has enabled me to better understand my journey as a Father, Coach, and citizen of the world God created. I am very passionate guiding and inspiring the youth, student-athletes, students, coaches, and teachers  and this course has empowered and equipped me to go out and guide others on their own journeys to transforming themselves by also understanding the 3D framework and approach and building their foundation to transform .

column18: Towards the end, it does tend to get a little repetitive.  I understand the need for solidifying ideas, but by module 22, we don't need to be reminded of the structure.
column19: Overall, this was a wonderful framework to base my coaching style on.  I have used some of these techniques in the past, but I don't believe I was intentionally a 3rd dimension type of coach.  With these suggestions and techniques, I really believe coaches can "up" their games, and influence young people in a very positive way.  The short sections, make this an easy program to get through.  You can leave it for a bit, and not lose any of the value.  In our busy lives, I really appreciate this type of format.  Thank you for putting this all together.

column7: Empower student athletes to maintain integrity while facing the diversity of life with a growth mindset.
column18: Adding a female coach to the mix would allow for another perspective for us female coaches out here.  I have coached both boys and girls and there is an emotional difference between them.  I do like how you added extra learning tools to our reading and podcast list. I think the Ted talk about "The Sexy Lie"  was right on with how girls feel at a high school level and into early college.  I don't think this topic needs to be added to the program, I just think that as a woman coach, it would be nice to associate with another woman in the field by hearing how this program has effected her coaching experience.
column19: Very good course!  I'm happy I took the time to slow down and listen to these messages.  Although I have been using some of these strategies without realizing it, I feel like the fragments of my coaching have been put into order.  I am excited to use some of these strategies in my program this year. Thank you to my athletic director for recommending this video.

column18: As a choir director that spends an exorbitant of time outside of school business hours, I think this course has a lot to offer.  However, it was entirely sports related.  A lot of it, I already do on a daily basis.  Some of it, either doesn't pertain to what I do, or needs to be modified to accommodate this.  Reaching students is the name of the game for me, and so I believed in this program long before I'd ever heard of it.  The planning section was a bit ridiculous to go through one by one.  Perhaps an overview page with a very short informational line about each one, so that "coaches" can go through the ones that would best suit their needs.  This was a very long course, and that section made it a bit ridiculous.
column19: Getting to know your student athletes, and in my case singers and dancers, is a must.  Students have to know how much you care about them before they will care how much you know to teach them.  This is a solid course in learning how to build and connect with students.

Through the week, we talked about what it takes to be a 3D coach, and here, my last assignment of graduate school is to deepen my knowledge of what it takes to be a 3D coach. How great is our God. This curriculum brought me to conviction, to tears, to overwhelming motivation and it truly humbled me as a coach, teacher and family man.  I am eager to continue my path to become a 3D coach and I have been provided with some tremendous resources now thanks to 3Dimensional Coaching.  This has been a blessing.

column6: FCA Philippines Regional Director for Southern Mindanao
column7: To influence leaders and marginalized people to journey toward the fullness of their God-given destinies by His grace, with a sense of great joy, and with generous hearts to serve others.
column18: I hope you can develop a more in-depth module on PTSD to help Coaches be a competent vehicle of God to use sports to bring healing to many children and youth who are suffering in many nations. I am a Licensed Environmental Planner with the desire to be more involved in the Social and Human Sciences Sector - under the United Nations Sustainable Development Goals with focus on Sports. I am a graduate of Human Ecology from the University of the Philippines and has been engaged as a Trainer-Consultant in Human Resource Development.
column19:
I praise the Lord for the gift of this course and the people behind its concept and design. It is well-developed and interactive making learning an enjoyable process. The 3D Coaching process relates very closely to my profession in Human Resource. Thank you for mentioning about children at risk.  

Engaging all the modules challenged me to revisit, revalidate and reaffirm my life's purpose, and the issues of faith, destiny, and legacy. I feel more confident and empowered in my involvement with FCA. God has a sovereign plan for Philippine sports. This course has blessed me so much. It will be my legacy to pass it on and transform sports in our country for the glory of God.

column7: To: Empower people to realize and act upon their relevance to others with empathy and dignity throughout their lives.
column18: Perhaps note some sports-specific resources or people who have successfully implemented the program. For example, I'd like to meet or resource with coach(es) in a mentor/'mentee' capacity for the sport of tennis...in a community or school setting where the sport is not especially a 'limelight' sport. Tennis is unique in that it is generally very individualized in play, and the 'team' concept can be hard to grasp for many players and coaches alike.
column19: Throughout my coaching career I have been viewed by others as being a successful coach, however my own assessment of the 'feeling(s)' at the end of the season have left me in discontent. Hopefully the ideals and content provided by this course will enable me to tie loose ends, and solidify my purpose as a coach. Because of my age I am nearing the end of my career, and wish I would have had this course many years ago, but I can implement things now....and plan to pass this content on to my children who have become coaches or leaders in their own realms. Thank you!

column7: To inspire girls to maximize their potential, become a loving basketball family, develop enthusiasm for the game, persevere through challenges, and do good for others.
column19: This program has provided me with the tools to move forward in as a fully capable, competent and inspired 3Dimensional Coach. To be honest, many of the foundations of 3D Coaching are already in my heart. I have always coached to the hearts and to the minds of my players. However, I would not in any way have considered myself an expert within the Level 2 and Level 3 realms of coaching. I knew I wanted to coach this way. I knew I had to coach this way. I even know why I wanted to coach this way. I did not know exactly how to coach this way, though. The strategies provided through 3Dimension Coaching will benefit my girls basketball players in ways I can't even imagine. The strategies will not only make me better as a coach, but also as a person. This program should be mandatory for any coach, for any person responsible with coaching and caring for players. Thank you so, so much for this opportunity. My life, and most importantly my players' lives, will be changed forever by this!

column18: It gets better every version
column19: Second time taking this course and it is better than the last version which I thought was impossible. I implemented these strategies since learning them. They are not really things we all don´t know.  Even more than that these are things that we as adults want but we forget, often, that the children we are charged with raising in our communities need these strategies more than we do. I am a firm believer in the power of serving others thanks in large part to this framework that puts what we already should know into a process we can use to better all those around us.

column7: I coach to forge men and women of honor who will compete on and off the field with faith, fervor, and fortitude.
column19:
Seeing and hearing Joe Ehrmann and Jeff Duke speak many years ago during keynote presentations at coaching conventions drastically improved my coaching skills.  The 3D Institute brings together the coaching philosophies of Jeff Duke, Joe Ehrmann, and many others and teaches it to coaches worldwide so they can effectively reach the hearts and minds of athletes.  

Over the years, I have implemented many 3D strategies and every single one of them have been wildly successful in positively shaping the cultures of the teams I have coached.  Any coach who is good enough to play a sport in college can pickup on any X's and O's they need to know in a day and many can talk about the X's and O's nonstop.  However, the more challenging task is forging strong leaders and shaping organizational culture.  Coaches who really want to develop leaders must be intentional about the process and the 3D framework shows you how to do so.  

I have seen too many coaches get into the game simply because they like the X's and O's.  Not every coach I know will be willing, committed, and intentional about leadership development to the level 3D demands.  The ones who are committed and intentional about leadership development will dominate the game and beyond.  

If I am ever the Head Coach of my own football program, 3D Coaching Certification will be mandatory for all of my assistants.  It is that good.  It is that necessary.

column19: God put this course in my life at the right time.  I did some of these principles and activities, but I was not intentional about it.  I was a 1D coach that spent little time in the 2nd and 3rd Dimensions.  Now I know that we all need to coach the 1st Dimension, but we need to be intentional about spending time in the 2nd and 3rd Dimensions.  This is where your team really bonds together and cares for each individual on and off the field.

column18: Man, I don't know what can be done to improve the course! Talk about transformational!
column19: Since becoming a coach at the age of 18, I've always known that my biggest weaknesses goes beyond teaching the fundamentals, the techniques, the movements of wrestling. I struggled year after year to find a way to fill the gaps in my coaching philosophies and practices. I'd had seasons when we nearly came out with top finishes for our program, and I'd had seasons when we nearly bottomed out. I always walked away with that bad taste in my mouth, that taste that would keep me up late at night questioning myself. Had I done the right things? Was I the right coach for this job? Was it time to step away and hand the reins to someone more able-bodied? Yet year after year, I received enough affirmations from parents and former wrestlers that I kept going. Through a series of difficulties and doubting moments, I happened to end up taking the 3 Dimension Coaching Course. I'm proud to say that much of WHAT I believed has been affirmed through the course, but even more so, I now have a much clearer idea and vision of HOW I can help my athletes. Thank you, from the bottom of my heart, for this incredible course.

column19: I had the privilege to hear Dr Duke speak at the NIAAA National Conference in Orlando FL a few years back and was amazed at the simplicity and truth of 3D Coaching.  In a world of quick fixes and "flavor of the month", the frameworks of 3D Coaching are a refreshing breath of truth.  It brings you back to core purpose of coaching.  It helps you as a coach remember the calling and passion of our profession.....developing the athlete as a complete person.  As an Athletic Director this helps align the "why" with the "what" and the "how".

column19: I believe wholeheartedly in 3D Coaching and what it will do for my athletes and the community that I am a part of. column18: The course itself is 5 stars.  I am a social worker at my high school but I am one of very few female coaches who coach boys soccer.  With that said, one improvement would be to have more diversity in the 3D instructors.  While there were females and minorities in some of the videos and pictures, it would enhance the program to have something other than a middle aged, Caucasian, southern, Christian male presenting the modules.  Again, the program speaks for itself and I do not doubt the validity of the men who presented, but that is my suggested improvement.

column7: Encourage students to act with confidence and joy on the field and in life
column18:
One thing I wished was different was that my transformational purpose statement never auto-populated. I am sure that the wording changed each time; that's not an automatically terrible thing, but I really focused on the first one and then it felt discarded. 
Also, perhaps it's me coming to this from a relatively cynical perspective, but I felt like the videos were too long and numerous and that I wasn't "inspired" in the way that the course or examples intended. When it got to the strategies, I had already been utilizing many. I guess I feel like teachers should already be practicing these concepts  and that the course must be more useful for non-educators.
Cultural homogeneity is still an issue.
Only a few of the resources were links to actionable sources (not just books on amazon), which was disappointing because the few that linked to websites were interesting.

column7: Have the Integrity to Teach and Model Greatness through Goodness to bring Wisdom and Joy to those I touch.
column18:
The presentation is hypocritical.  One of the key components focuses on intrinsic, not extrinsic, motivation in our lives and those we teach.  The entire presentation moves from extrinsic reward to the next (e.g. "Congratulations", "100% score", "You have completed ___".  This approach should be changed or altered.

The process is demeaning.  An intrinsically motivated, committed learner  does not need to take fill-in, true-false, etc. quizzes on what has just been presented in order to learn.  I found this unnecessary and offensive.

An individual who is committed to the 3D philosophy does not need a certificate, trophy or reward, in order to engage in a meaningful transformational process.  Again, this is hypocritical to the central focus of this course.
column19:
The content of this course is outstanding.  It reviewed and refreshed knowledge I already had.  It introduced a framework and a significant amount of new knowledge that will make be a better person, family member, and professional.  All of the speakers are outstanding -- knowledgeable, articulate, inspirational, and genuine.  The length of each segment seemed appropriate.  The ideas and resources provided will be valuable tools to use in the immediate and near future.  Thank you for all of the above!

As I stated earlier, please eliminate the hypocrisy of the extrinsic reward process and the demeaning quizzes along the way.  This will give the presentation and overall course much more credibility.

I am submitting this ONLY so you will receive my review and feedback, NOT for the certificate.

column18: I thoroughly enjoyed this course and as an athletic director would encourage all my coaches to take it.  The only suggestion I have is that there maybe needs to be some female perspectives and female examples.  Women and girls teams have unique issues that men and men's teams don't always deal with.  Male coaches need help dealing with female athletes.  It can be a strange new world for them if they are not prepared and in this day and age, male coaches need clear boundaries when dealing with women's teams.  Strategies that work with boys do not always work with girls and vise versa

I finally figured out how to navigate that section better but I don't think it was how it was suggested in the material.

column18: The course is excellent! Reason for not giving it 5 stars is that it is (understandably) geared for USA. I'm very interested to see what Cam Butler & Co. in Australia manage to do with the course to make it more culturally malleable and accessible for Scotland and UK. I'd be interested in seeing it geared more for Scotland and UK.
column19: The course is excellent! While geared primarily for the US sporting community the principles are clearly transferable and applicable to coaching in Scotland and the UK. With commitment to 3D principles and the imagination to ground them in your own country, the 3D coaching course can surely be a helpful and important resource in helping the worldwide community called 'Sport' to re-find its soul in situations where it has been buried under 'the way it's always been done', machismo and a 'win at all costs' mentality. 3D coaching helps us get beyond surface and skin-deep approaches to the heart of the matter "Who and Why Are You?"

column7: To mentor young people, through sport, to prepare them to become responsible citizens of a larger community.
column18: The vast majority of kids under the age of 12 are being coached by parent volunteers at Recreation Centers around the country. This course is wonderful for professional coaches who are dedicated to spending the time improving themselves and their craft. However, for Recreations Directors who are struggling just to fill coaching slots to get this information into the hands of these coaches, the ones who are doing the damage to the kids before we even see them, many of whom we never see as they have already dropped out of sports altogether, is a daunting task. Is there a way you could create a less intensive course that could at least begin the process for those in that situation?
column19: This course identified the issues facing coaches today and brought them together along with many suggestions for how to solve them. I would recommend it to any coach, those just starting out who wants a good framework for getting off on the right track as well as those who have been coaching for many years.

column7: We will lead our program to empower our athletes in body, mind and spirit so that they will lose with dignity, win with humility and learn to love being a part of something greater than themselves.

This course will revive the desire in the veteran coach and provide positive direction for the younger coaches. I am very excited to start implementing what I've learned. column19: Professional development is a necessity for educators and coaches. We all must continue to learn, grow, and exchange ideas with others. However, the focus of those sessions rarely reaches the personal level that it should. 3D Coaching does. When our coaches experienced 3D Coaching, there was substantial growth that took place. 3Dimensional Coaching focuses on the connections with kids and with people. It challenges coaches to get to the heart of an athlete. In my experience to date, I have not been a part of a more valuable professional development. As a result of this content, we implemented 3D Coaching Sessions that all coaches were welcome to attend. We met once a week for the remainder of the school year and are still doing so this summer. Those of us regulars have gotten a great deal from it. We have grown as coaches, and as people. I can't stress enough how beneficial 3Dimensional Coaching can be for you, your department or coaching staff.<blockquote style=margin: 0px 0px 0px 40px; padding: 0px; border: currentcolor; border-image-source: none;>Jason Kurz

column19: I would ABSOLUTELY recommend this course! I think a lot of my methods, tactics, and reasons for coaching were validated. It is nice. This course digs considerably deeper in ways to reach our kids and somewhat forces the coach to get an idea of how, what, why, etc. we should be coaching 3-dimensionally. I was intrigued, and subsequently, am a better coach already, having seen a fraction of 3D Coaching over the Summer at Silver College for USA Wrestling at University of Wisconsin. Incidentally, I was exposed to intrinsic vs. extrinsic motivation. I have competed nearly my entire life and never really 'got' how my own sons were never overly excited to wander around in their medals after a long tourney. Looking at the whole picture, I see that they are wrestling...for intrinsic purposes. They enjoy the competition, trying their takedowns, 'the sport,' and the 'game.' Knowing the difference, I am able to motivate much better, but, again, am validated in my own, already built, system for wrestling: (1.)FOUNDATION: We will build a foundation, fundamentally-strong, that will easily translate to any program, (2.) SUCCESS: We will help define success based on our athletes' unique skills/needs and, then, help them find it. (3.) FUN: perhaps, most-important, we will teach, learn, and compete in a way that is fun for all involved.

column19: I highly recommend this course for coaches. I definitely found the diamond among the roughs when it comes to coaching materials. Any coach can say, 'do this and that,' and you'll win guaranteed. However, this course teaches us that when you coach for developing the whole athlete (the spiritual, psychological, and physiological aspects), that's when you truly make a real difference in each of their lives. Learning about what it truly means to coach on the 2nd and 3rd dimension was the most valuable part. Skills that transcend coaching on the 1st dimension, which almost any coach can do. But coaching on the 2nd and 3rd dimension truly takes upstanding character, which we can cultivate and develop to produce other upstanding characters.
